issue_body:
When I have a must statement (statement-1) inside a grouping which is used by another grouping with a must statement (statement-2) which is used by the module then statement-1 is not applied during XML validation only statement-2.
Example:
```
$ cat main.yang 
module main {
    yang-version 1;
    namespace "http://example.com/main";
    prefix main;
    grouping inside-group {
        container must-test {
            must "must-test-1 = 1" {
                error-message "must inside grouping's grouping";
            }
            leaf must-test-1 {
                type uint8;
            }
            leaf must-test-2 {
                type uint8;
            }
        }
    }
    grouping group {
        container group {
            uses inside-group;
            must "must-test/must-test-2 = 1" {
                error-message "must inside grouping";
            }
        }
    }
    uses group;
}
$ cat test.xml 
<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<config xmlns="urn:ietf:params:xml:ns:netconf:base:1.0">
    <group xmlns="http://example.com/main">
        <must-test>
            <must-test-1>2</must-test-1>
            <must-test-2>2</must-test-2>
        </must-test>
    </group>
</config>
$ yang2dsdl -t config -v test.xml main.yang 
== Generating RELAX NG schema './main-config.rng'
Done.

== Generating Schematron schema './main-config.sch'
Done.

== Generating DSRL schema './main-config.dsrl'
Done.

== Validating grammar and datatypes ...
test.xml validates

== Adding default values... done.

== Validating semantic constraints ...
--- Failed assert at "/nc:config/main:group":
    must inside grouping
```
If I put a refine must statement (statement-3) after the uses inside-group statement then statement-1 is applied but statement-3 is duplicated in the dsdl file.
Example (the test.xml is the same):
```
$ cat main.yang
module main {
    yang-version 1;
    namespace "http://example.com/main";
    prefix main;
    grouping inside-group {
        container must-test {
            must "must-test-1 = 1" {
                error-message "must inside grouping's grouping";
            }
            leaf must-test-1 {
                type uint8;
            }
            leaf must-test-2 {
                type uint8;
            }
        }
    }
    grouping group {
        container group {
            uses inside-group {
                refine must-test {
                    must "must-test-1 = 1" {
                        error-message "must inside grouping refine";
                    }
                }
            }
            must "must-test/must-test-2 = 1" {
                error-message "must inside grouping";
            }
        }
    }
    uses group;
}
$ yang2dsdl -t config -v test.xml main.yang 
== Generating RELAX NG schema './main-config.rng'
Done.

== Generating Schematron schema './main-config.sch'
Done.

== Generating DSRL schema './main-config.dsrl'
Done.

== Validating grammar and datatypes ...
test.xml validates

== Adding default values... done.

== Validating semantic constraints ...
--- Failed assert at "/nc:config/main:group":
    must inside grouping
--- Failed assert at "/nc:config/main:group/main:must-test":
    must inside grouping refine
--- Failed assert at "/nc:config/main:group/main:must-test":
    must inside grouping's grouping
--- Failed assert at "/nc:config/main:group/main:must-test":
    must inside grouping refine
```
I think must statements should work independent of in which grouping it is defined or I missed something from the RFC.

Hi, Davis!
I made my own face detector using dlib dnn. I noticed that the performance of the detector falls dramatically if you feed images of different sizes. Moreover, in this case, it is not possible to efficiently parallelize the calculations on multiple gpus. As a result of profiling it became clear that the reason for the slowdown lies in the frequent calls of cudaMallocHost() function. I solved this problem by changing the method resizable_tensor::set_size(...) as follows:

```
diff --git a/dlib/dnn/tensor.h b/dlib/dnn/tensor.h
index 80d51ef..bcbb700 100644
--- a/dlib/dnn/tensor.h
+++ b/dlib/dnn/tensor.h
@@ -385,7 +385,8 @@ namespace dlib
             m_nr = nr_;
             m_nc = nc_;
             m_size = n_*k_*nr_*nc_;
-            data_instance.set_size(m_size);
+            if (data_instance.size() < m_size)
+                data_instance.set_size(m_size);
 #ifdef DLIB_USE_CUDA
             cudnn_descriptor.set_size(m_n,m_k,m_nr,m_nc);
 #endif
```

Is it the best way to solve this problem?

